THE third edition of the water, sanitation and hygiene and energy conference (WASHen 2016), kicks off today at the Zimbabwe International Trade Fair (ZITF) in Bulawayo with the focus being on innovative solutions for positive outcomes. BY MTHANDAZO NYONIRunning under theme Innovative solutions, positive outcomes the expo will centre on three thematic areas, which are public-private-partnerships in WASH infrastructure development; climate change, WASH and clean energy as well as information communication technology for development.The event is organised by ZITF Company in partnership with the Netherlands Development organisation (SNV Zimbabwe). It will see the introduction of practitioner s professionals working in the hygiene and renewable energy sectors can meet for the exchange of views, knowledge and information. The forums have been borne out of the realisation that just knowing how to do the work is insufficient. Practitioners must also have skills in mobilising resources and managing the relationship with clients, said ZITF company marketing and public relations manager, Stella Nkomo.Today, there is a conference on water, sanitation, hygiene and energy as well as practitioner s forum on menstrual hygiene management. Expected participants for the practitioner s forum are donor organisation representatives, implementing partners, local authorities, community members as well as representatives from the Ministries of Health and Child Care, Women Affairs, Gender and Community Development and Rural Development, Preservation and Promotion of Culture and Heritage.Tomorrow, there will be a renewable energy forum to discuss opportunities for private sector participation for mini grids in Gwanda.Representatives from Gwanda Rural District Council will present the available opportunities, while representatives from central government and the regulatory authority ZERA will clarify the policy issues.Environment, Water and Climate minister Oppah Muchinguri-Kashiri will be guest of honour at the two-day event.